Mark Twain </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=razberiswrl>razberiswrl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>fetus farmer</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 9:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  well</span><hr size=1> my sister has 2 adopted children that are bio siblings.  they have approx 12 other sibs in state care, all of the children are medically fragile or severely mentally challenged.  the state doesnt provide any incentive to keep this woman from breeding (she is severely mentally challenged herself), because of course it is wrong to sterilize her with out her permission.  <br>
<br>
anyway, my sister gives her $120 a year to stay on the depo shot, $30 for every shot.  im still not sure how i feel about this because this woman DOES NOT KNOW what shes being given.  she doesnt know what the shots are for.  my sister tells her its birth control, but the woman doesnt have any comprehension, shes in her 30s and prolly has the capacity of a 2nd grader.<br>
<br>
its such a fine line and there are no concrete answers. <br>
<br>
michelle <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 158<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 2:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Sterilization</span><hr size=1> Are we just talking about offering to pay for voluntary sterilization?  Involuntary sterilization or trickery is technically an invasion of someone's liberties, eventhough the end result would be good.  Offering to pay for voluntary sterilization is something that I support 100%.  So what if the donor isn't offering to get the woman off of drugs.  That isn't her mission.  That is like offering to buy groceries for a needy family, and then getting slammed because you aren't providing clothing that they need.  If someone is offering to help in one way, then they shouldn't get slammed for not doing everything in the world to help a person.  I think offering sterilization to these women is a noble gesture.  You are not only saving countless babies from harm and suffering, but you are also saving the woman some extra stress which can make it harder to kick her drug habit.  It is a nice thought to focus entirely on just getting the women off of drugs, but there is no guarantee they would stay off of drugs.  At least this way she would only be harming herself.  Regardless of whether you call addiction a disease or a choice, it still isn't the baby's fault, and they shouldn't have to suffer.  Let's save everyone the heartache and at least offer these women sterilization options.  <br>
<br>
On another note, if all of our healthcare options included birth control in their coverage, then that would also prevent such a high number of crack babies and such.  They'll pay for Viagra so the man could sleep with the woman, but they rarely pay for birth control so the woman can be protected when she is with her Viagra machine.  The reason so many low income women get pregnant is because they can't afford birth control, and those are also the same women who are more likely to turn to drugs.  I know drug use is rampant in all levels of society, but socioeconomics are a huge factor nonetheless.  Birth control coverage would not only save a fortune in health care for unwanted babies, but it would prevent a lot of these druggies from getting knocked up and harming their babies with continued drug use.  <br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> M2</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 2:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  sterilization</span><hr size=1> I think that temporary sterilization incentives (like money to stay on depo or something) sounds great.  I'm not sure permanent sterilization is the best idea, because who knows one day they may pull their head out, get off the drugs and decide that they would like a family.  It would be a shame to have a situation that they couldnt change if they chose to get their lives together.<br>
<br>
I think it would be financially better to offer to pay for birth control than to pay for the unwanted pregnancies and foster care for brain injured children from druggie moms.  Ethically, I would be happy that these children would not have to be concieved and born by mothers who care nothing for them to the point of injuring them. <br>
<br>
Thats my 2 cents! - Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=doublelatte>Double Latte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Got Milk?</span><br>  Posts: 157<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 3:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: sterilization</span><hr size=1> I'll donate!<br>
<br>
I think it's a great idea as long as it is voluntary. That's the key. I also agree that it's unfair to slam anyone providing birth control services or incentives. You can't solve someone else's drug addiction, but you can help them stop making fragile babies that they can't even take care of in the first place.<br>
<br>
I thought health departments offered low-cost birth control for the poor.<br>
<br>
DL <p>&quot;Beware of a clear and present evil in the name of some future, nebulous good.&quot;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> sweetpeas mommy</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 3:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  torn on this one...</span><hr size=1> I guess I am torn on this one...on the one hand, I am glad that this will stop babies from being born into sad lives where they suffer from drugs and neglect. On the other hand, while programs like these may solve one symptom of the problem, they do nothing for the larger issue of drug addiction. And you can be pretty sure, a lot of the money paid to the women for sterilization is used to buy more drugs. Drugs in society lead to more than just unwanted babies. Overall, I guess I don't mind the idea of sterilization so much but I wish that our country had a more comprehensive way to deal with drugs.<br>
<br>
And yes, DL, I think most Health departments offer free or low cost condoms to anyone who wants them...<br>
<br>
Kerrie-Anne <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 159<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 4:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  $$$$$</span><hr size=1> &quot;And you can be pretty sure, a lot of the money paid to the women for sterilization is used to buy more drugs.&quot;<br>
<br>
There can be safeguards in place that make sure the money is going directly to the doctors or clinics providing birth control or sterilization.  We have an audit client that helps low income families pay for rent and utilities, and one year my boss found a check to an apartment complex that was washed, and the person cashed it at the liquor store.  Our client did a total overhaul of the process once this was discovered.  Now they make sure the landlord is getting the checks, and not the liquor stores.  A program for BC/sterilization can pay doctors and clinics directly so the money doesn't end up in the hands of the druggies.  If an organization was to just blindly hand the money to the drug addict, then they may as well give up because they would just be contributing to the problem.  I'm sure there would be some screw ups, but a responsible organization would follow through, and if they were to receive federal funds within their organization, then they would need to run a tight ship anyway.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=powertotherae>Powertotherae</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Satan's Lil' Minion</span><br>  Posts: 274<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/12/03 9:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: $$$$$</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;And you can be pretty sure, a lot of the money paid to the women for sterilization is used to buy more drugs.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually she would only give the money to them after they brought her a note form the Dr. Most of the women chose to have permant sterilization done. That is the only part I don’t agree with just because they aren’t in the right mind to make such a long-term decision. Then again they aren’t in the right frame of mind to have a baby.<br>
<br>
